WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:01:30.000
This is Jacob's Research Journal. Today's deep dive: The Accidental Longevity Drug. In November 2023, the SELECT trial reported that semaglutide reduced major adverse cardiovascular events by 20% in adults with obesity but without diabetes. Then cardiologists found a 40% relative risk reduction for heart failure. Then kidney specialists found a 16% reduction in kidney failure risk. One drug. Not four. And none of these outcomes were what it was designed for.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:03:15.000
GLP-1 receptor agonists were built to manage blood sugar in type 2 diabetes. They were not designed to extend life or intervene in the biology of aging. But Nature Biotechnology asked: Are GLP-1s the first longevity drugs? To appreciate why GLP-1s matter for aging, you need to understand how barren the longevity landscape has been. Resveratrol faded. NAD+ precursors produced minimal clinical evidence. Senolytics are only now entering early human trials. The TAME metformin trial still can't raise its budget after a decade.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:06:30.000
Rapamycin has the strongest preclinical pedigree but the data in humans have yet to establish it as a proven therapeutic. Less than 1% of industry-sponsored trials in 2025 were geroscience trials. The clinical evidence for GLP-1s is substantial. LEADER: 13% MACE reduction. SUSTAIN-6: 26%. SELECT: 20% in non-diabetic obesity. A 40% relative risk reduction for heart failure. Kidney failure risk reduced by 16%. Liver inflammation resolved in 63% of patients. Inflammation marker CRP reduced by 38%.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:08:30.000
GLP-1 receptor agonists appear to intervene in at least five of the twelve hallmarks of aging: deregulated nutrient sensing, chronic inflammation, cellular senescence, mitochondrial dysfunction, and intercellular communication. Nature Biotechnology called GLP-1s the closest thing to what the longevity field has long sought in a gerotherapeutic. Compared with previous candidates, there are vastly more human data for GLP-1s.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:11:00.000
But there is a genuine problem. In STEP 1 trials, roughly 39% of weight lost was lean body mass. The Harvard Science Review reported this risks creating sarcopenic obesity. A drug that reduces multiple hallmarks of aging may simultaneously accelerate one of them. 82.6% of patients aged 75 and older discontinued within 24 months. GLP-1s are merely a metabolic catalyst, not standalone treatments.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:12:30.000
The safety profile: gastrointestinal events cause 6.5% discontinuation. Retained gastric contents in 56% of users. Gallstone risk increases by 46%. A signal for thyroid carcinoma exists but absolute risk is low. Good news: no causal link to pancreatitis, and no association with serious psychiatric effects across 80 trials.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:14:15.000
The global GLP-1 market is projected at $58 billion in 2026 and could exceed $180 billion by 2035. Reinsurers Munich Re and Swiss Re are pricing GLP-1 mortality effects into their models. When actuaries change mortality assumptions, it signals the all-cause mortality reductions are real enough to price.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:15:30.000
The honest assessment: GLP-1s produce clinically meaningful reductions across multiple organ systems. The all-cause mortality reduction is probably real. But no GLP-1 trial has been designed with aging as an endpoint. The longevity case is built on secondary analyses. GLP-1s are not proven longevity drugs. Nature Health argues they should be rigorously tested as longevity therapeutics. That has not happened yet.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:16:38.550
What to watch: next-generation GLP-1 analogs with reduced lean mass loss, whether regulators recognize aging as treatable, addiction trial results in late 2026, and independent replication. The most important longevity drug candidate of 2026 was not built by gerontologists. It arrived by accident, carried by a hundred-billion-dollar market that did not need regulatory approval for aging because it already had it for everything else. Full post and sources at jacobbrooke95.github.io/jacobs-research-journal.
